I went to Army Cadets for a portion of time, and cut to go on a camp that did FieldCraft outside (which was my favourite thing to do other than disassembly of the rifles) and when we had our MREs we didnt have those heat packs, we had to cook our food stuff in a metal pot over an open flame.

Also, everyone got hard boiled sweets in theirs, and me being the lucky charm I am, got a pack of fizzy cola bottles. It was great. I was once and shared though because I felt bad

snippet.textDisplay: Hearing the temperature that the MRE's are warmed to gives me a big ol' YIKES!. It's smack in the middle of the Temperature Danger Zone (41F to 135F), which is the prime temperature for bacterial growth. Bacterial growth does also include viral growth as most viruses are just a fast growing bacteria. This could probably cause issues in third-world countries that have foreign diseases and are too poor for treatment, as if the MRE's are in that temp then the bacteria will grow. Unless the food on the inside is vacuum sealed, this could be a big reason on why military people get sick.

snippet.textDisplay: Here's something you could try. I have made a "torch" from an MRE heater that doesn't self destruct. You need a small piece of metal tubing the tinier the better. You seal off the bag, poke a hole with the tube and tape it so it is sealed. You can then light the end of the tube and it will have a sustained flame like a torch. I never tried multiple heaters in one pack though, that would be interesting to see.

snippet.textDisplay: I once had one spontaneously self ignite and no amount of water would put it out, it just made more and more hydrogen keeping it on fire. That was a sad day out in the freezing snow with my only meal. Kinda disappointed that not all of the fun things we used to do were tried. My favorite was to put a couple heaters into a water bottle and fill it some of the way with water, give her a shake and throw. The effect will yield varying results based on lots of parameters such as water volume and bottle size/composition but the best result should be similar to a big fire cracker.
